lf-expression, Cox shows, are key to the residents exercising their agency, while their creation of alternative family structures demands a rethinking of notions of care, protection, and love. Cox also uses these young women's experiences to tell larger stories: of Detroit's history, the Great Migration, deindustrialization, the politics of respectability, and the construction of Black girls and women as social problems. With Shapeshifters Cox gives a voice to young Black women who find creative and non-normative solutions to the problems that come with being young, Black, and female in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAfrican American girlszMichiganzDetroit. 0aAfrican American homeless persons - Michigan - Detroit. 0aAfrican American homeless personszMichiganzDetroit. 0aHomeless girlszMichiganzDetroit. 4aAAA section award winners. 4aCritical Study of North America award winner. 4aDelmos Jones and Jagna Sharff Memorial Book Prize winner. 4aSociety for Anthropology of North America book awards. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375371zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375371.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles